issue_comments.body:
@dougbu 

If you make each assembly responsible for adding the services it owns, you still need to bootstrap that somehow.

``` C#
Microsoft.AspNet.Mvc.Razor.Services.Add(services);
Microsoft.AspNet.Mvc.Rendering.Services.Add(services);
Microsoft.AspNet.Mvc.ModelBinding.Services.Add(services);
Microsoft.AspNet.Mvc.ViewHost.Services.Add(services);
```

etc.

I was thinking that we'd have another assembly that references all dependencies needed to wire up the default stack. Basically the code in the sample would be in the default MVC wire up stack would be implemented away from user code. 

We also need to think about the cross framework scenario. Remember there's a single container for Mvc, SignalR, Data, etc. 

Each of those frameworks will provide default services into some container:

``` C#
public class Startup
{
    public void Configuration(IBuilder builder)
    {
       var provider = new ServiceProvider();

       // This code can be cleaned up but it shows the idea
       Mvc.PopulateServices((interfaceType, implType, singleton) => provider.Add(interfaceType, implType));
       Data.PopulateServices((interfaceType, implType, singleton) => provider.Add(interfaceType, implType));
       SignalR.PopulateServices((interfaceType, implType, singleton) => provider.Add(interfaceType, implType));

       // Wire up the provider that will be used for middleware
       builder.UseServiceProvider(provider);

       var routes = new RouteTable();

      var mvcConfiguration = new MvcConfiguration(serviceProvidr);

       routes.MapMvcRoute(...., mvcConfiguration);
       builder.MapSignalR();
       builder.UseRoutes(routes);
    }
}
```

